      <text>
        The first hill is deceptive. From the boundary clearing it looked gentle — just a slope with some rocks. But now that I'm climbing it, my legs are discovering every way "gentle slope" is a lie. The angle keeps changing, the ground shifts under my boots — loose stone skitters away with every step. And there's this fun new element called "elevation" that makes my lungs work harder than they did in the flat wetlands or the forest.

        Oakshade says, "Steady pace. The hills reward patience, not speed."

        I'm learning that Oakshade says everything like it's profound wisdom. Maybe when you're a tree, everything is _profound_ — different timescale, different perspective.

        Mossmantle says, "Rock to your left is loose — step right instead. Better foundation."

        Mossmantle's voice is lower, earthier, like stones settling; Oakshade's is deep and resonant, like wind through branches. Between them I'm getting philosophical, big-picture advice _and_ practical step-by-step instructions — it's actually kind of perfect.

        I step right and the rock holds.

        I say, "Thanks, Mossmantle."

        Scout bounces past me up the slope, clearly delighted by this terrain. Hills mean opportunities — uphill bouncing, downhill rolling, rocks to investigate. The little sphere is having the time of their life.

        Oakshade observes, "Scout's adapted well to elevation. Momentum serves them differently here."

        See — profound. But here's the thing — I'm adapting too. Not as effortlessly as Scout, but way better than I would have a week ago. My body knows the rhythm of walking all day; my pack sits balanced on my shoulders. I'm watching the terrain, reading the guides' cues, adjusting my pace without thinking about it.

        In adventure shows, the protagonist gets a training montage and suddenly they're competent at everything. Real life — well, real life on an alien planet being guided by sentient plants — doesn't work like that. But nine days of walking, nine days of learning to trust the process, actually does something. I'm not struggling anymore. I'm just… walking.

        ¶

        The realization makes me smile.

        Oakshade says, "You're pleased."

        I say, "I'm good at this now — the walking part. I didn't expect to be good at it."

        Oakshade replies, "Growth happens gradually — like rings in bark. Each day adds a layer."

        Mossmantle makes a soft, textured chuckle.

        Mossmantle says, "Oakshade always talks about rings — Moss doesn't have rings — we just spread and deepen. Different growth."

        Oakshade says serenely, "Both valid paths."

        I'm starting to understand their dynamic. Oakshade thinks in years and patterns and big concepts. Mossmantle thinks in inches and immediate problems and what's right in front of you. They balance each other — tree wisdom and ground-level practicality.
      </text>
