        Different from Leafwhisper and Rootwalker's information-versus-silence, different from Streamwalker and Brightbloom's calm-versus-energy — every guide pair has their own language. And I'm learning to speak all of them.
        ¶
        The slope levels off into a plateau. I stop to catch my breath and turn to look back the way we came. The wetlands are visible in the distance — flat and glittering with water, a completely different terrain. We've climbed higher than I realized.

        Oakshade says, "The view expands with elevation — distance provides perspective."

        I say, "It's beautiful."
        And it is — purple sky reflecting in the wetland pools, the darker line of forest beyond. Three territories, three completely different worlds.

        Mossmantle checks the path ahead and says, "Another three hours to tonight's rest area — two more climbs, both steeper. Water source at the campsite."

        Right — beautiful views are nice, but we still have to keep walking. I take a long drink from my water supply, Scout bounces back from their exploration, and we continue.

        The afternoon is all hills: up one slope, down the other side, up the next. My legs burn — not the sharp pain of injury but the deep ache of muscles working hard. It's different from forest walking or wetland slogging. Everything engages — calves for pushing uphill, thighs for controlling downhill, core for balance on uneven ground.

        Buddy says, "Kira, your heart rate is elevated! This is excellent cardiovascular exercise. Did you know that hill climbing engages sixty percent more muscle groups than level terrain walking —"

        I say, "I can feel that, Buddy — physically feeling it right now."

        Buddy says, "Oh — of course. Apologies — you're doing very well."

        I blink. That was... just supportive. Not a teaching moment. Just genuine encouragement.

        "Thanks, Buddy," I say.

        Buddy is learning too.

        Scout finds something interesting — a cluster of crystalline rocks that catch the light. They bounce excitedly, rolling around the formation, clearly wanting me to see it.

        But it's not just excitement. I recognize the pattern now: the discovery bounce, the same rhythm Scout used when they found the water sources in the forest, the same energy as when they warned me about the steep bank and led me around hazards. This is Scout's intelligence-gathering dance — find something, return, show it, bounce until the human pays attention.

        I say, "Very pretty, Scout."
        And something shifts in my chest. Scout found this and brought it to me. That's what they _do_.

        Scout bounces — not just agreement, but something warmer. Validated, as if they've been waiting for me to understand.

        Mossmantle says, "They form from mineral deposits — water seeps through and leaves minerals behind. It takes many cycles."

        Oakshade adds, "Patience crystallized — slow processes creating lasting beauty."
      </text>
